data.content:
Yes — modern MSTest (v3.4+) supports **tuple-based `DynamicData`**, eliminating the `object[]` indirection:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:** The data source returns `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` instead of `IEnumerable<object[]>`. MSTest automatically destructures the tuple into the test method parameters.

**Benefits:**
- Compile-time type checking on test data — adding `(123, false)` would be a compiler error
- Named tuple elements improve readability
- No boxing of value types like `bool`

Requires **MSTest 3.4+** (`MSTest.TestFramework` / `MSTest.TestAdapter` NuGet packages).
